explanation: OS_CHECK_POINTER: Macro used at the top of the function — could contain code that reassigns the pointer parameter or performs other side effects. Its definition is required to prove the pointer variable queue_prop is not modified by the macro. OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET: Macro used to obtain the record from the global table — its expansion must be inspected to ensure it does not reference or assign to queue_prop. OS_global_queue_table: The table operand used by OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET; needed to expand/understand the macro behavior and ensure no indirect modification of queue_prop. OS_queue_prop_t: The pointee type definition (structure) is required to confirm that only the object pointed-to is modified (fields via memset/strncpy) and to check for any hidden pointer members or aliasing that could affect the pointer parameter itself. OS_common_record_t: Definition of the record type returned from the table lookup; needed to verify the fields accessed (name_entry, creator) and to ensure those accesses do not alias or cause hidden assignments to queue_prop. OS_object_token_t: Type of token passed into object-id APIs and used by the table-get macro; included to inspect any macros or APIs that might store state back into caller-supplied pointers. memset: Standard library function called with queue_prop as destination — its semantics must be known to confirm it modifies the object pointed-to but not the pointer variable itself. strncpy: Standard library function used to copy into queue_prop->name — required to show it modifies the pointee, not the pointer parameter. OS_ObjectIdGetById: Called before using the token/table — its implementation or specification is needed to ensure it does not modify the queue_prop parameter (e.g., via side-effects or aliasing). OS_ObjectIdRelease: Called before return — needed to verify it does not alter the queue_prop parameter. Together, these symbols let an analyst expand macros and inspect called routines to determine whether any of them reassign the pointer parameter (queue_prop) itself (which would violate the MISRA rule) versus only modifying the object pointed to (which is allowed).
